│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe core of the problem lies in the         │
│ `select` instruction within your loop:\n`%narrow.i = select i1 %cmp1.i, i32 1, i32         │
│ %iv`\n\nHere, `%cmp1.i` is true when the induction variable `%iv` is even.\n- If `%iv` is  │
│ even, `%narrow.i` becomes `1`.\n- If `%iv` is odd, `%narrow.i` becomes `%iv`.\n\nThe       │
│ legacy cost model correctly identifies that when `%iv` is odd, `%narrow.i` takes the value │
│ of `%iv`. It then models the cost of the subsequent multiplication (`%red.next = mul nsw   │
│ i64 %red, %mul`) as a vector-scalar multiplication, which is generally expensive. Based on │
│ this high cost, it decides that vectorization is not profitable and chooses a              │
│ Vectorization Factor (VF) of 1 (i.e., no vectorization).\n\nThe VPlan-based cost model,    │
│ however, makes a different determination. It uses Scalar Evolution (SCEV) to analyze the   │
│ value of `%narrow.i`. It concludes that `%narrow.i` can be represented by the SCEV         │
│ expression `(1 + (2 * %iv))`, which is always odd. This is a crucial simplification.       │
│ Because the value is always odd, the VPlan cost model believes it can potentially optimize │
│ the multiplication. This leads it to calculate a lower cost for vectorization and select a │
│ VF of 2.\n\nThe discrepancy between the legacy model's VF=1 and the VPlan model's VF=2     │
│ triggers the assertion, because the framework expects the models to agree unless the VPlan │
│ finds a specific, recognized simplification (which isn't the case here).\n\n### 2.         │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log and backtrace point directly to                     │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF()`. This is the function responsible for          │
│ evaluating various vectorization factors and picking the best one. The assertion failure   │
│ within this function confirms that the final decision-making process is where the          │
│ inconsistency between the two cost models is caught.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe  │
│ root cause is the VPlan cost model's over-aggressive simplification of the `select`        │
│ instruction's value using SCEV. While it's mathematically true that the value of           │
│ `%narrow.i` is always odd, the VPlan cost model fails to account for the fact that this    │
│ value is derived from the induction variable itself.\n\nThe legacy model correctly         │
│ penalizes the use of the induction variable in the multiplication, leading to a high cost  │
│ estimate. The VPlan model, by simplifying `%narrow.i` to an abstract SCEV expression,      │
│ loses this crucial context. It no longer sees the direct dependency on the induction       │
│ variable and thus underestimates the cost of vectorizing the multiplication.\n\nThe fix is │
│ to make the VPlan cost model aware of this situation. When evaluating the cost of an       │
│ instruction, if an operand is a `select` whose value depends on the induction variable, we │
│ should not rely solely on its simplified SCEV expression. Instead, we should use the cost  │
│ of the `select` instruction itself, which more accurately reflects the complexity of the   │
│ operation that needs to be vectorized.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nTo implement    │
│ this fix, I will modify the `getOperandCost` function in `VPlanCostModel.cpp`. This change │
│ will ensure that if an operand is a `select` instruction that is part of the vectorization │
│ plan (i.e., a \"recipe\"), we use the cost of the `select`'s recipe instead of trying to   │
│ compute a cost from its SCEV expression.\n\n```cpp\n//                                     │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanCostModel.cpp\n\n/// If \\p V is a uniform value,       │
│ return 0. If \\p V is a recognizable\n/// uniform-like value (e.g. a constant vector),     │
│ return a cost estimate for\n/// materializing it. Otherwise, return the cost of the recipe │
│ that computes\n/// \\p V.\nInstructionCost VPlanCostModel::getOperandCost(const VPValue    │
│ *V,\n                                               const VPInstruction *User) {\n  if     │
│ (isa<VPReplicateRecipe>(V->getDef())) {\n    const VPReplicateRecipe *RepR =               │
│ cast<VPReplicateRecipe>(V->getDef());\n    if (RepR->isUniform())\n      return 0;\n\n     │
│ // The operand is a vector that is broadcasted from a scalar.\n    // Check if the scalar  │
│ is a constant or a value that can be uniformly\n    // held in a vector register.\n    if  │
│ (isScalarWithSmallMaterializationCost(RepR->getOperand(), User))\n      return             │
│ TTI.getScalarizationOverhead(RepR->getOperand()->getType(),\n                              │
│ AP_Uniform, AP_Whatever);\n  }\n\n  // If the operand is a Select, we may have a SCEV      │
│ expression for it, but\n  // we should still use the cost of the select recipe itself.\n   │
│ if (auto *Def = V->getDef())\n    if (auto *SelectR = dyn_cast<VPSelectRecipe>(Def))\n     │
│ return getRecipeCost(SelectR);\n\n  // Try to estimate the cost based on the SCEV value.\n │
│ if (auto *C = getSCEVValue(V))\n    if (auto Cost = getSCEVOperandCost(C))\n      return   │
│ *Cost;\n\n  // Fallback to the recipe cost.\n  return                                      │
│ getRecipeCost(V->getDef());\n}\n```\n\nThis change is targeted and minimal. By checking    │
│ for a `VPSelectRecipe` early in `getOperandCost`, we ensure that the true cost of the      │
│ `select` is used, preventing the VPlan cost model from being misled by the simplified SCEV │
│ expression. This will align its cost estimation with the legacy model for this specific    │
│ case, resolving the assertion failure."})                                                  │
