│ instruction's value depends on the loop's induction variable (`%iv`). The loop also        │
│ contains a multiplication that uses the result of this `select`:\n`%red.next = mul nsw i64 │
│ %red, %mul` (where `%mul` is derived from `%narrow.i`)\n\nThe two cost models in the loop  │
│ vectorizer evaluate this scenario differently:\n- The **legacy cost model** correctly      │
│ identifies that using the induction variable as an operand in a multiplication is          │
│ expensive to vectorize. It therefore concludes that vectorization is not profitable and    │
│ chooses a Vectorization Factor (VF) of 1 (i.e., no vectorization).\n- The **VPlan-based    │
│ cost model** uses Scalar Evolution (SCEV) to analyze the `select`. It simplifies the       │
│ expression for `%narrow.i` and, in doing so, loses the crucial information that one of the │
│ `select`'s arms is the induction variable itself. This over-simplification leads it to     │
│ underestimate the cost of the multiplication. As a result, it incorrectly determines that  │
│ vectorization is profitable and chooses a VF of 2.\n\nThis disagreement in the chosen VF   │
│ (1 vs. 2) triggers the assertion `VPlan cost model and legacy cost model                   │
│ disagreed`.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe backtrace clearly shows the crash       │
│ occurs in `llvm::LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF()`. This function is responsible  │
│ for comparing the costs of different vectorization strategies. The assertion at            │
│ `LoopVectorize.cpp:7369` is specifically designed to catch disagreements between the new   │
│ VPlan cost model and the legacy one during the transition period, which is exactly what is │
│ happening here.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root of the problem lies in the       │
│ `cost` function for `VPInstruction` within `VPlan.cpp`. When calculating the cost of an    │
│ instruction (like the `mul`), it calls `getOperandCost` for each of its operands.\n\nThe   │
│ `getOperandCost` function attempts to use SCEV to find a cheap, symbolic cost for an       │
│ operand. In this case, it successfully gets a SCEV expression for the `select`'s output    │
│ but fails to recognize the high underlying cost because the induction variable is one of   │
│ the `select`'s inputs.\n\nThe correct behavior is to recognize when an operand is itself a │
│ complex instruction (like a `select`) that is part of the vectorization plan and to use    │
│ the cost of that instruction's \"recipe\" directly, rather than relying on a potentially   │
│ misleading SCEV simplification.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to modify   │
│ `VPInstruction::cost` in `VPlan.cpp`. We will add a check to see if an operand is defined  │
│ by a `VPSelectRecipe`. If it is, we will use the cost of that recipe directly instead of   │
│ proceeding to the more general `getOperandCost` function which might get misled by         │
│ SCEV.\n\nThis ensures that the cost of the `select` operation, which correctly accounts    │
│ for its operands (including the induction variable), is factored into the cost of the user │
│ instruction (the `mul`).\n\nHere is the proposed edit:\n\n```cpp\n// In                    │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp\n\nInstructionCost                                 │
│ VPInstruction::cost(ElementCount VF, VPCostContext &CostCtx) {\n  InstructionCost C = 0;\n │
│ for (const VPValue *V : operands()) {\n    // If the operand is a Select, we may have a    │
│ SCEV expression for it, but\n    // we should still use the cost of the select recipe      │
│ itself.\n    if (auto *Def = V->getDef())\n      if (auto *SelectR =                       │
│ dyn_cast<VPSelectRecipe>(Def)) {\n        C += CostCtx.getRecipeCost(SelectR);\n           │
│ continue;\n      }\n    C += CostCtx.getOperandCost(V, this);\n  }\n  return               │
│ C;\n}\n```\n\nThis change correctly propagates the cost of the `select` to its users,      │
│ aligning the VPlan cost model with the legacy model for this case and resolving the        │
│ assertion.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nBy ensuring the VPlan cost model properly accounts for  │
│ the cost of `select` instructions that depend on the induction variable, we fix the        │
│ underestimation that led to the erroneous decision to vectorize. This change makes the     │
│ VPlan cost model more robust and brings its results in line with the legacy model, thereby │
│ fixing the crash."})                                                                       │
